{{note|1|1}} The alveolar trill ({{IPA|/r/}}) is [[Syllabic consonant|syllabic]] between two consonants; for example, {{angbr|прст}} {{IPA|[ˈpr̩st]}} 'finger'. The dental nasal ({{IPA|/n/}}) and dental lateral ({{IPA|/ɫ/}}) are also syllabic in certain foreign words; e.g. {{angbr|њутн}} {{IPA|[ˈɲutn̩]}} '[[Newton (unit)|newton]]',  {{angbr|Попокатепетл}} {{IPA|[pɔpɔkaˈtɛpɛtɫ̩]}} '[[Popocatépetl]]', etc.

The [[labiodental nasal]] {{IPA|[ɱ]}} occurs as an allophone of {{IPA|/m/}} before {{IPA|/f/}} and {{IPA|/v/}} (e.g. {{angbr|трамвај}} {{IPA|[ˈtraɱvaj]}} '[[tram]]'). The [[velar nasal]] {{IPA|[ŋ]}} similarly occur as an allophone of {{IPA|/n/}} before {{IPA|/k/}} and {{IPA|/ɡ/}} (e.g. {{angbr|англиски}} {{IPA|[ˈaŋɡliski]}} 'English'). The latter realization is avoided by some speakers who strive for a clear, formal pronunciation.

==Phonological processes==
At morpheme boundaries (represented in spelling) and at the end of a word (not represented in spelling), voicing opposition is [[Final-obstruent devoicing|neutralized]].

==Stress==
The [[word stress]] in Macedonian is [[wikt:antepenultimate|antepenultimate]], meaning it falls on the third from last [[syllable]] in words with three or more syllables, and on the first or only syllable in other words. This is sometimes disregarded when the word has entered the language more recently or from a foreign source. The following rules apply:
* [[Disyllabic]] words are stressed on the second-to-last syllable.

For example, {{angbr|дете}} {{IPA|[ˈdɛtɛ]}} 'child', {{angbr|мајка}} {{IPA|[ˈmajka]}} 'mother' and {{angbr|татко}} {{IPA|[ˈtatkɔ]}} 'father'.
* [[Trisyllabic]] and [[polysyllabic]] words are stressed on the third-to-last syllable.

For example, {{angbr|планина}} {{IPA|[ˈpɫanina]}} 'mountain', {{angbr|планината}} {{IPA|[pɫaˈninata]}} 'the mountain' and {{angbr|планинарите}} {{IPA|[pɫaniˈnaritɛ]}} 'the mountaineers'.

Exceptions include:
* [[Participle|Verbal adverbs]] (i.e. words suffixed with {{angbr|-ќи}}): e.g. {{angbr|викајќи}} {{IPA|[viˈkajci]}} 'shouting', {{angbr|одејќи}} {{IPA|[ɔˈdɛjci]}} 'walking'.
* Foreign [[loanword]]s: e.g. {{angbr|клише}} {{IPA|[kliˈʃɛ]}} 'cliché', {{angbr|генеза}} {{IPA|[ɡɛˈnɛza]}} 'genesis', {{angbr|литература}} {{IPA|[litɛraˈtura]}} 'literature', {{angbr|Александар}} {{IPA|[alɛkˈsandar]}}, '[[Alexander]]' (Possibly based on hellenised variations of indigenous Bryges and/or Enchele naming conventions){{Citation needed|date=February 2018}}, etc.

