{{BLP sources|date=July 2010}}
[[File:Michael Lev 2.jpg|thumb|right|160px|Michael Lev]]'''Michael (Mishe) Lev''' (3 July 1917 - 23 May 2013) was a [[Yiddish language]] writer.

Lev was born in [[Pohrebysche]],<ref name="intro">Krutikov, Mikhail.[https://books.google.com/books?id=AoJgBm9mrAwC&pg=PR9 Michael Lev, Sobibor, and Soviet Yiddish Culture], Introduction to ''Sobibor'' (2007)</ref> Ukraine.  He studied Yiddish language and literature in Moscow, and worked at a Yiddish publishing house, where his first publications appeared. During [[World War II]] Lev fought in the Russian army, was taken prisoner, escaped, and joined the partisans.<ref name="intro"/>  His wartime experiences became the main theme of his writings.  He published 17 books in Yiddish, Russian and Hebrew.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yiddish.forward.com/articles/170145/in-memory-of-misha-lev/ |title=צום אָנדענק פֿון מישע לעוו ע״ה |publisher=yiddish.forward.com |date= |accessdate=2013-05-26}}</ref>  He died, aged 95, in Rehovot, Israel.

