{{distinguish|Tamanic languages}} {{Infobox language family |name=Tamangic |region=[[Nepal]] |familycolor=Sino-Tibetan |fam2=[[Tibeto-Kanauri languages|Tibeto-Kanauri]] ? |child2=[[Ghale languages|Ghale]] |child1=Tamangic proper |child3=[[Kaike language|Kaike]] |glotto=kaik1248 |glottorefname=Kaike–Ghale–Tamangic }}
The '''Tamangic languages''', '''TGTM languages''', or '''West Bodish languages''', are a family of [[Sino-Tibetan languages]] spoken in the Himalayas of [[Nepal]]. They are called West Bodish by Bradley (1997).
==Languages== The languages are: *[[Tamang language|Tamang]] (several divergent varieties, with a million speakers) *[[Gurung language|Gurung]] (two varieties with low mutual intelligibility) *[[Thakali language|Thakali]] (including the Seke dialect; ethnically Tamang) *[[Manang language|Manang]] language cluster: the closely related [[Manang language|Manang]], [[Gyasumdo language|Gyasumdo]], [[Nar Phu language|Nar Phu]], and [[Nyeshangte language|Nyeshangte]] languages. *[[Chantyal language|Chantyal]] *[[Ghale languages]] ([[Ghale language|Ghale]] and [[Kutang language|Kutang]]): spoken by ethnic Tamang, perhaps related to Tamangic. *[[Kaike language|Kaike]] (moribund): may be the most divergent.
==Classification== Tamangic is united with the [[Bodish languages|Bodish]] and [[West Himalayish languages]] in Bradley's (1997) "Bodish" and Van Driem's (2001) [[Tibeto-Kanauri languages|Tibeto-Kanauri]].
==Reconstruction== Proto-TGTM has been reconstructed in Mazaudon (1994). (Note: '''TGTM''', which is another name used to refers to the Tamangic branch, stands for [[Tamang language|'''T'''amang]]-[[Gurung language|'''G'''urung]]-[[Thakali language|'''T'''hakali]]-[[Manang language|'''M'''anang]].)
